Survival analysis by TP53 and telomerase activity

  • Setup
  • Prepare data for modeling
  • Univariate Models
    • Extent of tumor resection
    • TP53
    • Telomerase score
    • LGG or HGG group
    • Cancer group (cox)
    • Cancer group (log rank)
  • Multivariate models
    • Interaction model: tp53_score*telomerase_score*extent_of_tumor_resection*lgg_group
    • Additive model: tp53_score+telomerase_score+extent_of_tumor_resection+lgg_group
    • Interaction model: tp53_score*telomerase_score*extent_of_tumor_resection*hgg_group
    • Additive model: tp53_score+telomerase_score+extent_of_tumor_resection+hgg_group
    • Additive models: tp53_score+telomerase_score+extent_of_tumor_resection for each cancer group
  • Session Info

Note that for models that consider the cancer_group predictor or are performed separately for each cancer group only consider cancer groups where DECEASED >= 3. There are seven such groups.

Setup

Packages and functions

library(survival)
library(ggpubr)
library(tidyverse)

Set up files and directories

Set up input and output directories:

root_dir <- rprojroot::find_root(rprojroot::has_dir(".git"))

data_dir <- file.path(root_dir, "data")
analysis_dir <- file.path(root_dir, "analyses")

tp53_dir <- file.path(analysis_dir, "tp53_nf1_score")
telomerase_dir <- file.path(analysis_dir, "telomerase-activity-prediction")

results_dir <- "results"
plots_dir <- "plots"
util_dir <- "util"

if (!dir.exists(results_dir)) {
  dir.create(results_dir)
}
if (!dir.exists(plots_dir)) {
  dir.create(plots_dir)
}

Source the util function file.

# Source functions used to build and export models
source(file.path(util_dir,"survival_models.R"))

Set up file paths.


# Define input files:
metadata_file <- file.path(data_dir, "pbta-histologies.tsv")

# These analyses consider only stranded libraries:
tp53_file <- file.path(tp53_dir, 
                        "results", 
                        "tp53_altered_status.tsv")

tel_stranded_file <- file.path(telomerase_dir,
                               "results",
                               "TelomeraseScores_PTBAStranded_FPKM.txt")

Prepare data for modeling

Import and process the metadata

# Will remove the below patients because I do not know if they had total or partial resections until we check with Jenn Mason

# 7316-116 has Biopsy only;Gross/Near total resection
# 7316-182 has Gross/Near total resection;Partial resection

# get primary tumor and remove cell lines
histologies_rna <- read_tsv(metadata_file, guess_max = 10000) %>%
  filter(composition=="Solid Tissue",
                  tumor_descriptor == "Initial CNS Tumor",
                  experimental_strategy == "RNA-Seq", 
                  RNA_library == "stranded") %>%
  rename(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID_RNA = Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID) %>% 
  # clean up extent of tumor resection
  mutate(extent_of_tumor_resection = case_when(
    extent_of_tumor_resection == "Biopsy only;Gross/Near total resection" ~ "Gross/Near total resection",
    extent_of_tumor_resection == "Gross/Near total resection;Partial resection" ~ "Gross/Near total resection",
    extent_of_tumor_resection == "Not Reported" ~ "Unavailable",
    TRUE ~ as.character(extent_of_tumor_resection))) %>%
  select(Kids_First_Participant_ID, Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID_RNA, sample_id, cancer_group, OS_status, OS_days, PFS_days, extent_of_tumor_resection) %>%
  filter(sample_id != "7316-116" & sample_id != "7316-182") %>%
  distinct()

# combine tp53 scores and telomerase score to the dataframe
# note that we do not need to recode categories since the survival_models.R functions will take care of it
meta_indep <- histologies_rna %>%
  # add tp53 and telomerase scores by matching Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID_RNA
  left_join(tp53_scores, by = "Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID_RNA") %>%
  left_join(tel_scores, by = "Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID_RNA") %>% 
  rename(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID = Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID_RNA) %>%
  distinct(Kids_First_Participant_ID, .keep_all=TRUE) %>%
  # remove samples without survival data
  drop_na(OS_days) %>%
  # convert to years
  mutate(OS_years = OS_days / 365.25)

# Show the data we will use for analysis
meta_indep

# remove lgg
meta_indep_no_lgg <- meta_indep %>%
  filter(cancer_group != "Low-grade glioma astrocytoma")

# remove tumors fully resected
meta_indep_no_resect <- meta_indep %>%
  filter(extent_of_tumor_resection != "Gross/Near total resection")

Create subsets of data for different models

We create two new tibbles from meta_indep:

  • meta_indep_grouped which contains new columns hgg_group that contains levels (in order) non-HGG and HGG indicating whether it’s a HGG sample and lgg_group that contains levels (in order) non-LGG and LGG indicating whether it’s a LGG sample
  • meta_indep_cancers which is subsetted to only certain cancer groups of interest that have suitable sample sizes which we find here.
# Define LGG and HGG groups
hgg_cancer_groups <- c("High-grade glioma astrocytoma", "Diffuse midline glioma", "Diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma") 
hgg_levels <- c("non-HGG", "HGG")
lgg_levels <- c("non-LGG", "LGG")

# separate into HGG or non-HGG and make the new column a factor
meta_indep_grouped <- meta_indep %>% 
   mutate(hgg_group = ifelse(cancer_group %in% hgg_cancer_groups,
                             hgg_levels[2], # second is HGG 
                             hgg_levels[1]), # first is non-HGG
          hgg_group = factor(hgg_group, levels = hgg_levels), # ensures non-HGG is the reference level
          lgg_group = ifelse(cancer_group == "Low-grade glioma astrocytoma",
                             lgg_levels[2], # second is HGG 
                             lgg_levels[1]), # first is non-HGG
          lgg_group = factor(lgg_group, levels = lgg_levels) # ensures non-HGG is the reference level
   )
# Define cancer groups of interest with higher Ns
# We want to only include groups that have at least THREE in the DECEASED category. 
# Find them here:
cancer_groups_of_interest_df <- meta_indep %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  count(cancer_group,OS_status) %>%
  spread(OS_status, n,
         # When there are no events, record the event count as 0 instead of the default NA
         fill = 0) %>%
  filter(DECEASED >= 3) 
# show result: there are 7 groups to keep
cancer_groups_of_interest_df

# Subset to only the cancer groups with potentially suitable sample size
meta_indep_cancer_groups <- meta_indep %>%
  filter(cancer_group %in% cancer_groups_of_interest_df$cancer_group) %>%
  # set reference level to Medulloblastoma
  mutate(cancer_group = fct_relevel(cancer_group, "Medulloblastoma"))

# How many patients got removed?
nrow(meta_indep) - nrow(meta_indep_cancer_groups)
[1] 317

Univariate Models

Here, we run a survival analyses for several independent predictors, one at a time. We use cox regression for all analyses (including categorical), as demonstrated in survival-analysis_template.Rmd.

  • extent_of_tumor_resection (categorical)
  • tp53_score (continuous)
  • telomerase_score (continuous)
  • lgg_group (categorical)
  • hgg_group (categorical)
  • cancer_group (categorical)

Extent of tumor resection

Confirming gross/near total tumor resection has a very significant prognostic effect. The greater the resection, the better the OS.

# full dataset

              "extent_of_tumor_resection",

Cancer group (log rank)

Here, we perform a log-rank analysis specifically for the cancer_group predictor, using data that only considers the 7 cancer groups determined to have suitable sample sizes (DECEASED >= 3). The output below shows:

  • Table of model coefficients
  • Matrix of Pairwise comparisons using Log-Rank test, which shows which cancer groups are significantly different from one another

Note that confidence intervals are so large that survival plots are not clearly legible, so we don’t make that visualization here.


# Print model coefficients
fit_save_model(meta_indep_cancer_groups,
               "cancer_group",
               file.path(results_dir,
                         "log_rank_survival_per_cancer_group.RDS"),
               test = "log.rank")
Testing model: survival::Surv(OS_years, OS_status) ~ cancer_group with cox.reg
# Compare pairwise with Bonferroni correction for multiple testing
survminer::pairwise_survdiff(survival::Surv(time = OS_years, event = OS_status) ~ cancer_group,
                             meta_indep_cancer_groups %>% mutate(OS_status = ifelse(OS_status == "LIVING", 0, 1)), 
                             p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")

Multivariate models

Background on hazard ratios and output, from ref:

"Hazard ratio above 1 indicates a covariate that is positively associated with the event probability, and thus negatively associated with the length of survival.

In summary,

HR = 1: No effect HR < 1: Reduction in the hazard HR > 1: Increase in Hazard"

The Cox regression results can be interpreted as follow: Statistical significance. The column marked “z” gives the Wald statistic value. It corresponds to the ratio of each regression coefficient to its standard error (z = coef/se(coef)). The wald statistic evaluates, whether the beta (β) coefficient of a given variable is statistically significantly different from 0. From the output above, we can conclude that the variable sex have highly statistically significant coefficients.

The regression coefficients. The second feature to note in the Cox model results is the the sign of the regression coefficients (coef). A positive sign means that the hazard (risk of death) is higher, and thus the prognosis worse, for subjects with higher values of that variable. The variable sex is encoded as a numeric vector. 1: male, 2: female. The R summary for the Cox model gives the hazard ratio (HR) for the second group relative to the first group, that is, female versus male. The beta coefficient for sex = -0.53 indicates that females have lower risk of death (lower survival rates) than males, in these data.

Hazard ratios. The exponentiated coefficients (exp(coef) = exp(-0.53) = 0.59), also known as hazard ratios, give the effect size of covariates. For example, being female (sex=2) reduces the hazard by a factor of 0.59, or 41%. Being female is associated with good prognostic.

Confidence intervals of the hazard ratios. The summary output also gives upper and lower 95% confidence intervals for the hazard ratio (exp(coef)), lower 95% bound = 0.4237, upper 95% bound = 0.816.

Global statistical significance of the model. Finally, the output gives p-values for three alternative tests for overall significance of the model: The likelihood-ratio test, Wald test, and score logrank statistics. These three methods are asymptotically equivalent. For large enough N, they will give similar results. For small N, they may differ somewhat. The Likelihood ratio test has better behavior for small sample sizes, so it is generally preferred.

Below, HR = exp(coeff)

int_lgg

Interaction terms are not significant, except tp53_score:telomerase_score at \(P=0.0272866\), which does not change much from individual term p-values, suggesting an additive model is more appropriate.

Additive model: tp53_score+telomerase_score+extent_of_tumor_resection+lgg_group

The strongest predictor here is extent of tumor resection with gross/near total resection having a survival benefit and partial resection nearing significance for a survival benefit. High TP53 scores, telomerase scores, and non-LGG are all significant risk factors for poorer overall survival.

# we save this for the purpose of printing out a p-value below

Additive model: tp53_score+telomerase_score+extent_of_tumor_resection+hgg_group

HGG group:HGG and high telomerase scores are significant risk factors for poorer overall survival. Extent of tumor resection: gross/near total is a survival advantage. High TP53 scores trend toward a significant risk for poorer overall survival.

Additive models: tp53_score+telomerase_score+extent_of_tumor_resection for each cancer group

The EPN model shows significant effects for both tp53_score and telomerase_score. The DMG model is marginally significant for tp53_score only.

base_filename <- "cox_per_cg_terms_tp53_telomerase_resect.RDS" # all file names here will follow this convention

for (cg in cancer_groups_of_interest_df$cancer_group) {
  cat("==============", cg, "==================")
  # filter to cancer group of interest
  fit_data <- meta_indep %>% 
    filter(cancer_group == cg)
  
  # Define filename where model will be saved
  filename <- file.path(
    results_dir,
    str_replace(base_filename, "cg", cg)
  )
  
  # Fit model
  fit_save_model(fit_data, 
                 "tp53_score + telomerase_score + extent_of_tumor_resection", 
                 filename, 
                 model_type = "multivariate") %>% print()
}
